sql:
SELECT MAX(experiment_count) AS highest_experiment_count
FROM (
  SELECT COUNT(experiment_id) AS experiment_count
  FROM experiments
  GROUP BY user_id
);

external_knowledge:
- "Multiple experiments" refers to users who have conducted more than one experiment;
- "Average performance" is calculated by averaging the performance metric values across all runs of the experiments;
- "Best to worst" means the results are ordered by the average performance in descending order.

- "Most recent experiments" refers to the latest experiments in each session, determined by the creation timestamp;
- "Successfully completed" means the experiment has a status of 'completed';
- "Performance metric" is a value that quantifies how well the model performs, typically higher values indicate better performance.

- 'stands tall' refers to the model with the highest average performance metric value;
- 'completed projects' refers to experiments with a status of 'completed';
- 'TensorFlow-trained model' refers to models that used the TensorFlow framework.

- The "most recent experiment sessions" refers to the latest date in the `formatted_date` column;
- "Performance and configuration" are inferred from the `max_step`, `min_walltime`, `max_value`, and `min_smoothed` columns in the `ExperimentDetails` CTE;
- "Configuration" includes the average batch size used in each experiment.

- The specific timestamp is 1570050000.0, which corresponds to a certain date and time;
- The smoothed performance metric threshold is 0.98;
- The wall time is the Unix timestamp representing the time when the experiment run was completed.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT experiment_id) AS experiment_count
FROM experiment_runs
WHERE status = 'completed';

external_knowledge:
- "Top 5 most promising models" refers to the models with the highest average performance metric values in their most recent runs;
- "Latest performance" refers to the performance metric value from the most recent run of each model;
- "Most robust seedlings" is a metaphor for the best-performing models.

sql:
SELECT experiment_id
FROM experiment_runs
WHERE f1_score = (SELECT MAX(f1_score) FROM experiment_runs);

